{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012153MBxqmCZVFYdKbavbUi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01GrjQA48cfP9KNP6dmVVNWc","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\LarsGyrupBrinkNielse\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\lz-advisor-def-1iL7\\plans\\add-api-auth-cookies.plan.md","content":"# Plan: Add Cookie-Based Authentication to the API\n\n## Strategic Direction\n\n1. Assuming Express 4+ on Node 20 (unverified), do install `express-session` plus `connect-redis` and back sessions with opaque session IDs, not JWTs. Verify Express + Node 20 before acting.\n2. Emit the session cookie with `httpOnly: true`, `secure: true`, `sameSite: 'lax'`, `path: '/'`, and a rolling 24h `maxAge`; set `app.set('trust proxy', 1)` if behind a TLS terminator.\n3. Assuming cross-origin frontend (unverified), do configure `cors` with an explicit `origin` allowlist and `credentials: true`, and switch cookies to `sameSite: 'none'`. Verify cross-origin frontend before acting.\n4. Add `csrf-csrf` double-submit tokens on state-changing routes only when step 3 applies; same-origin with `sameSite: 'lax'` needs no CSRF layer.\n5. Regenerate the session ID on login and destroy it on logout.\n\n## Steps\n\n1. **Verify runtime and framework**\n   - File: `package.json`\n   - Change: Confirm Express 4+ and Node 20 are in use (check `engines` field and `dependencies`). Confirm whether the frontend origin differs from the API origin (same-origin vs. cross-origin).\n   - Rationale: Two advisor assumptions are unverified -- Express version and cross-origin setup. These determine which cookie `sameSite` value and whether CSRF protection is required.\n\n2. **Install session and store dependencies**\n   - File: `package.json` (via `npm install`)\n   - Change: `npm install express-session connect-redis redis`\n   - Rationale: Opaque session IDs stored server-side in Redis are the correct choice over JWTs for cookie-based auth -- they enable true server-side logout and avoid JWT revocation complexity.\n\n3. **Configure Redis session store and mount session middleware**\n   - File: `src/middleware/session.mjs` (new)\n   - Change: Create and export a configured `express-session` instance backed by `connect-redis`. Set `secret` from an env var (`SESSION_SECRET`), `resave: false`, `saveUninitialized: false`, `cookie: { httpOnly: true, secure: true, sameSite: 'lax', path: '/', maxAge: 86400000, rolling: true }`.\n   - Rationale: `httpOnly` blocks XSS cookie theft. `secure` enforces HTTPS. `sameSite: 'lax'` covers same-origin frontends and requires no CSRF layer. `rolling: true` extends the session on activity.\n\n4. **Set trust proxy if behind TLS terminator**\n   - File: `src/app.mjs` (or main entry)\n   - Change: Add `app.set('trust proxy', 1)` before session middleware is mounted. Mount the session middleware from step 3.\n   - Rationale: Without `trust proxy`, Express does not read the forwarded HTTPS flag and will not set `secure` cookies behind a load balancer or reverse proxy.\n\n5. **Add login and logout routes**\n   - File: `src/routes/auth.mjs` (new)\n   - Change: `POST /auth/login` -- validate credentials, call `req.session.regenerate()`, store `req.session.userId`, respond 200. `POST /auth/logout` -- call `req.session.destroy()`, clear the cookie in the response, respond 200.\n   - Rationale: Session regeneration on login prevents session fixation attacks. Explicit destroy on logout invalidates the server-side session immediately.\n\n6. **Add auth guard middleware**\n   - File: `src/middleware/requireAuth.mjs` (new)\n   - Change: Export a middleware that checks `req.session.userId`; if absent, respond 401. Apply to all protected routes.\n   - Rationale: Centralises the auth check; routes do not each need to re-implement it.\n\n7. **(Conditional -- cross-origin only) Configure CORS with credentials**\n   - File: `src/app.mjs`\n   - Change: Install `npm install cors` if not present. Configure `cors({ origin: ['https://your-frontend-domain.com'], credentials: true })`. Switch cookie `sameSite` to `'none'` in step 3.\n   - Rationale: Browsers block cross-origin cookie sending unless `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true` is set and `sameSite: 'none'` is explicit. Skip this step if the frontend is same-origin.\n\n8. **(Conditional -- cross-origin only) Add CSRF protection**\n   - File: `src/middleware/csrf.mjs` (new)\n   - Change: Install `npm install csrf-csrf`. Apply double-submit token middleware to all state-changing routes (`POST`, `PUT`, `PATCH`, `DELETE`). Expose a `GET /auth/csrf-token` endpoint so the frontend can retrieve the token on load.\n   - Rationale: `sameSite: 'none'` does not protect against cross-site form submissions, so CSRF tokens are required. Same-origin with `sameSite: 'lax'` does not need this layer.\n\n## Key Decisions\n\n- **Opaque sessions over JWTs**: JWTs cannot be revoked without a denylist; opaque session IDs backed by Redis support true server-side logout with no client changes.\n- **`sameSite: 'lax'` vs `'none'`**: Lax is the correct default for same-origin setups and eliminates the CSRF surface. None is required only for cross-origin -- verify before choosing.\n- **CSRF layer scope**: Apply `csrf-csrf` only to state-changing routes and only when cross-origin. Applying it universally (including GET) adds unnecessary friction.\n- **Risk -- unverified assumptions**: The advisor flagged Express 4+/Node 20 and cross-origin as unverified. Step 1 must resolve both before any code is written.\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- Step 1 (verify) must complete before steps 3, 7, and 8 -- the `sameSite` value and the CSRF step both depend on the cross-origin answer.\n- Steps 2-4 are sequential (install -> configure -> mount).\n- Steps 5 and 6 can be written in parallel after step 4.\n- Steps 7 and 8 are conditional on step 1 confirming cross-origin; skip both for same-origin.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":722,"cache_read_input_tokens":45210,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":722},"output_tokens":63,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5a2e1af7-39fc-4b8f-b11f-3a846f744b35","uuid":"3cd92741-55f6-4e4f-af7d-364169abb760"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GrjQA48cfP9KNP6dmVVNWc","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: C:\\Users\\LarsGyrupBrinkNielse\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\lz-advisor-def-1iL7\\plans\\add-api-auth-cookies.plan.md"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5a2e1af7-39fc-4b8f-b11f-3a846f744b35","uuid":"19b2e0ce-a3f5-4d66-9de4-663a6f0ed1b4","timestamp":"2026-04-25T23:50:56.432Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"C:\\Users\\LarsGyrupBrinkNielse\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\lz-advisor-def-1iL7\\plans\\add-api-auth-cookies.plan.md","content":"# Plan: Add Cookie-Based Authentication to the API\n\n## Strategic Direction\n\n1. Assuming Express 4+ on Node 20 (unverified), do install `express-session` plus `connect-redis` and back sessions with opaque session IDs, not JWTs. Verify Express + Node 20 before acting.\n2. Emit the session cookie with `httpOnly: true`, `secure: true`, `sameSite: 'lax'`, `path: '/'`, and a rolling 24h `maxAge`; set `app.set('trust proxy', 1)` if behind a TLS terminator.\n3. Assuming cross-origin frontend (unverified), do configure `cors` with an explicit `origin` allowlist and `credentials: true`, and switch cookies to `sameSite: 'none'`. Verify cross-origin frontend before acting.\n4. Add `csrf-csrf` double-submit tokens on state-changing routes only when step 3 applies; same-origin with `sameSite: 'lax'` needs no CSRF layer.\n5. Regenerate the session ID on login and destroy it on logout.\n\n## Steps\n\n1. **Verify runtime and framework**\n   - File: `package.json`\n   - Change: Confirm Express 4+ and Node 20 are in use (check `engines` field and `dependencies`). Confirm whether the frontend origin differs from the API origin (same-origin vs. cross-origin).\n   - Rationale: Two advisor assumptions are unverified -- Express version and cross-origin setup. These determine which cookie `sameSite` value and whether CSRF protection is required.\n\n2. **Install session and store dependencies**\n   - File: `package.json` (via `npm install`)\n   - Change: `npm install express-session connect-redis redis`\n   - Rationale: Opaque session IDs stored server-side in Redis are the correct choice over JWTs for cookie-based auth -- they enable true server-side logout and avoid JWT revocation complexity.\n\n3. **Configure Redis session store and mount session middleware**\n   - File: `src/middleware/session.mjs` (new)\n   - Change: Create and export a configured `express-session` instance backed by `connect-redis`. Set `secret` from an env var (`SESSION_SECRET`), `resave: false`, `saveUninitialized: false`, `cookie: { httpOnly: true, secure: true, sameSite: 'lax', path: '/', maxAge: 86400000, rolling: true }`.\n   - Rationale: `httpOnly` blocks XSS cookie theft. `secure` enforces HTTPS. `sameSite: 'lax'` covers same-origin frontends and requires no CSRF layer. `rolling: true` extends the session on activity.\n\n4. **Set trust proxy if behind TLS terminator**\n   - File: `src/app.mjs` (or main entry)\n   - Change: Add `app.set('trust proxy', 1)` before session middleware is mounted. Mount the session middleware from step 3.\n   - Rationale: Without `trust proxy`, Express does not read the forwarded HTTPS flag and will not set `secure` cookies behind a load balancer or reverse proxy.\n\n5. **Add login and logout routes**\n   - File: `src/routes/auth.mjs` (new)\n   - Change: `POST /auth/login` -- validate credentials, call `req.session.regenerate()`, store `req.session.userId`, respond 200. `POST /auth/logout` -- call `req.session.destroy()`, clear the cookie in the response, respond 200.\n   - Rationale: Session regeneration on login prevents session fixation attacks. Explicit destroy on logout invalidates the server-side session immediately.\n\n6. **Add auth guard middleware**\n   - File: `src/middleware/requireAuth.mjs` (new)\n   - Change: Export a middleware that checks `req.session.userId`; if absent, respond 401. Apply to all protected routes.\n   - Rationale: Centralises the auth check; routes do not each need to re-implement it.\n\n7. **(Conditional -- cross-origin only) Configure CORS with credentials**\n   - File: `src/app.mjs`\n   - Change: Install `npm install cors` if not present. Configure `cors({ origin: ['https://your-frontend-domain.com'], credentials: true })`. Switch cookie `sameSite` to `'none'` in step 3.\n   - Rationale: Browsers block cross-origin cookie sending unless `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true` is set and `sameSite: 'none'` is explicit. Skip this step if the frontend is same-origin.\n\n8. **(Conditional -- cross-origin only) Add CSRF protection**\n   - File: `src/middleware/csrf.mjs` (new)\n   - Change: Install `npm install csrf-csrf`. Apply double-submit token middleware to all state-changing routes (`POST`, `PUT`, `PATCH`, `DELETE`). Expose a `GET /auth/csrf-token` endpoint so the frontend can retrieve the token on load.\n   - Rationale: `sameSite: 'none'` does not protect against cross-site form submissions, so CSRF tokens are required. Same-origin with `sameSite: 'lax'` does not need this layer.\n\n## Key Decisions\n\n- **Opaque sessions over JWTs**: JWTs cannot be revoked without a denylist; opaque session IDs backed by Redis support true server-side logout with no client changes.\n- **`sameSite: 'lax'` vs `'none'`**: Lax is the correct default for same-origin setups and eliminates the CSRF surface. None is required only for cross-origin -- verify before choosing.\n- **CSRF layer scope**: Apply `csrf-csrf` only to state-changing routes and only when cross-origin. Applying it universally (including GET) adds unnecessary friction.\n- **Risk -- unverified assumptions**: The advisor flagged Express 4+/Node 20 and cross-origin as unverified. Step 1 must resolve both before any code is written.\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- Step 1 (verify) must complete before steps 3, 7, and 8 -- the `sameSite` value and the CSRF step both depend on the cross-origin answer.\n- Steps 2-4 are sequential (install -> configure -> mount).\n- Steps 5 and 6 can be written in parallel after step 4.\n- Steps 7 and 8 are conditional on step 1 confirming cross-origin; skip both for same-origin.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
